03905nam a22005295i 9780822386377DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20042004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223863777 a10.1515/97808223863772doi  a(DE-B1597)567634  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0070002bisacsh1 aWilkinson, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSilence on the Mountain :bStories of Terror, Betrayal, and Forgetting in Guatemala /cDaniel Wilkinson; ed. by Gilbert M. Joseph, Emily S. Rosenberg. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (389 p.) :b14 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican encounters/global interactions : 3900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tI. A House Burned -- tII. Ashes Fell -- tIII. A Future Was Buried -- tIV. And They Were the Eruption -- tList of Names -- tNote on Sources -- tSelected Bibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  anew in paperbackSilence on the Mountain is a virtuoso work of reporting and a masterfully plotted narrative tracing the history of Guatemala's thirty-six-year internal war, a conflict that claimed the lives of some 200,000 people, the vast majority of whom died (or were "disappeared") at the hands of the U.S.-backed military government. Written by Daniel Wilkinson, a young human rights worker, the story begins in 1993, when the author decides to investigate the arson of a coffee plantation's manor house by a band of guerrillas. The questions surrounding this incident soon broaden into a complex mystery whose solution requires Wilkinson to dig up the largely unwritten history of the country's recent civil war, following its roots back to a land reform movement that was derailed by a U.S.-sponsored military coup in 1954 and to the origins of a plantation system that put Guatemala's Mayan Indians to work picking coffee beans for the American and European markets.Decades of terror-inspired fear have led the Guatemalans to adopt a survival strategy of silence so complete that it verges on collective amnesia. The author's great triumph is that he finds a way for people to tell their stories, and it is through these stories-dramatic, intimate, heartbreaking-that we are shown the anatomy of a thwarted revolution that has relevance not only to Guatemala but also to countless places around the world where terror has been used as a political tool.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aGuerrillasxHistoryzGuatemala. 0aGuerrillaszGuatemalaxHistory. 0aState-sponsored terrorismzGuatemala. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Central America.2bisacsh1 aJoseph, Gilbert M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRosenberg, Emily S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822386377zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822386377423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822386377/original  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles